2026-04-16 12:10:33 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contacts', 'control module output wiring between relay and output cables'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the power supply is healthy (~12 V at its output) and correctly applied to the control module input. Inside the control module the node feeding the relay contacts is at ~11.99 V, but the node on the contact’s output side—and thus the control output (+) cable to the load—is clamped at about 0.36 V even when the relay should be closed and ambient light is steady. The low but non‑zero voltage at the output with no ripple is characteristic of a high‑resistance or partially open path at the relay contact or its immediate wiring/solder joints (e.g., pitted/oxidized contact, misaligned armature, or cracked trace). Initially the contact likely made intermittent connection, causing the lamp to blink off briefly every ~20 s; after the timing pot adjustment and further operation, the contact has degraded or shifted so that it now fails to close properly and the output sits at the ~0.36 V leakage level. Replacing/repairing the relay contact set or the short wiring/PCB trace from the relay output terminal to the control output (+) cable should restore full 12 V to the load and normal lamp operation.'
