2026-04-16 12:11:22 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor / light‑dependent element in control module', 'sensor bias / threshold network components in control module (associated with the ambient sensor input node)'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU delivers a solid ~12 V, and both the positive and negative control‑module rails reaching the relay contact are correct. Yet the relay output sits permanently at about 0.36 V, while the logic/sensor node is clamped close to ground (~0.12 V) and does not respond meaningfully to ambient light or potentiometer adjustments.\n\nContinuity on the negative rail is normal, and repairing/replacing the relay contacts and output wiring had no effect, ruling out a load‑side or contact fault. The elevated low‑level voltages (0.12–0.36 V) appear as small drops along the return path of the sensor/logic and coil, consistent with very small current through a path that is being held near ground by a faulty front‑end rather than by the relay/contact section.\n\nThe only remaining consistent explanation is that the ambient‑light sensing front end (LDR/photo‑diode or similar) and/or its immediate bias/threshold network has failed such that the sensor node is effectively shorted or heavily leaked to ground. That permanently drives the comparator so that the relay never sees a valid ‘on’ drive, leaving the relay output at the observed ~0.36 V and the lamp off, regardless of light level or timing settings.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a defect in the ambient sensor element or its associated bias/threshold components in the control module, not in the relay contacts, wiring, or PSU. Replacing the ambient sensor and its small bias/threshold network in the control module should restore proper operation.'
